<br>
I think Herndon's ideas are interesting but astrophysicists would take issue with his insistence on nuke-ignited stars. Stars have been pretty successfully modelled and the Standard Solar Model when checked against helioseismic data is accurate to within ~ 0.1%. A high-Z core, as described by Herndon, is pretty much ruled out. <br>
<br>
Jovian planets are much bigger unknowns since we can't observe things like seismic waves or neutrinos from their deep interiors so they might be nuke-powered. But the gravitational contraction mechanism isn't ruled out either since helium &quot;rain-out&quot; in their hydrogen mantles is an alternative source of power. <br>
<br>
I think Wayne wasn't as even-handed as he could have been. Herndon's ideas need a lot more data before they can seriously challenge the status quo.<br>
